                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I meant to look at this thread earlier. I saw it and had it open but left for work and one thing after another I didn't get to look at it till now two days after you posted. 
<br />

<br />
Big question is do you already have a monitor? This impacts every part of the system you will buy. Really. I mean, a decent 21" monitor will run you 200 bucks at the least which means you only have about 1300 for your computer itself system but if you already have a good monitor you can spend the full amount on the computer itself. And if you're thinking of a 19" gaming lcd that's going to run you at least 500 clams. 
<br />

<br />
Another big question is how fast do you plan to buy your system? Is it a pressing need now or can you wait two-three months? 
<br />

<br />
I'm going to assume you already have a viable monitor for your gaming purposes and that you can wait a bit since you said you are planning to build it in the near future and not soon. 
<br />

<br />
First we're going with an Athlon64 and not a P4. One, A64's run a tad cooler. The latest P4 designs were called prescotts but nicknamed pres-hots if that tells you how warm and toasty those new P4's get. I also like the A64's because they have the 64 bit extensions on the chip and if you choose to run a 64bit operating system like Linux or Windows 64 (currently in beta) at a later date you can do so without needing an upgrade. $205 AMD Athlon 64 3000+ is what I recommend. It's pretty much the bottom of the heap as far as A64 processors go but I feel the higher speed versions are simply not worth the money you spend would need to shell out for it. 
<br />

<br />
Now that we have our processor choice out of the way we head onto the motherboard. I'm recommending you wait 2-3 months till the new Nforce4 based motherboards come out. The majority of the features of the Nforce4 are the same as an Nforce3 based motherboard or VIA K8T800Pro based ones for that matter. However there are two huge differences which are PCI-X along with SLI. With the coming years there are going to be less and less AGP based motherboards and more and more PCI-X based ones. SLI is also shaping up to be one exciting technology. Click the link and check <a href="http://www.anandtech.com/video/showdoc.aspx?i=2258" target="_blank" class="postlink">this article</a> for what type of performance benefit SLI can give you. And keep in mind this was on a beta motherboard with beta drivers. This means that it is not yet working on optimizations for performance, only stability. This is why I recommend the wait. Currently these motherboards based on the Nforce4 are not out so I'm assuming it's in the 130-200 dollar range though. 
<br />

<br />
As far as IDE or SATA hard drive performance goes nothing beats the Raptor. Unless you're getting a RAID setup. You can always add a 3-400MB second hard drive later. The 74GB Raptor should be more than enough to load plenty of games and apps until you get a secondary hard drive. $182 with $2 shipping Western Digital Raptor 74GB.
<br />

<br />
As far as a case goes. I'm recommending an el-cheapo $50'ish one. Just find one that you like that isn't too bad. You might have to do further research on particular cases to see which is better. Not all cases are created equally. Find one that is roomy inside and aesthetically pleasing to you outside. Don't worry about what I or anyone else finds pleasing to the eyes. This is your computer. Get one that suits you and only you. And of course there is my dream case the <a href="http://www.newegg.com/app/viewproductdesc.asp?description=11-129-144&DEPA=0" target="_blank" class="postlink">Antec P160</a> which is simply beautiful but it's a pocket breaking $120 with $16 shipping. Another awesome case (and probably a better overall case from a technical standpoint) is the<a href="http://www.newegg.com/app/ViewProductDesc.asp?description=11-112-055&depa=0" target="_blank" class="postlink">Lian Li PC-V1200</a> case. It is very nice looking at a back breaking $210 with $16 shipping.
<br />

<br />
Power Supply. Man, get <a href="http://www.antec.com/us/productDetails.php?ProdID=24480" target="_blank" class="postlink">Antec NeoPower 480</a> because Antec is an awesome company and that modular designed power supply simply rocks. This is what I'm planning to put in my new system. It's $115 from Newegg. My current secondary choice would point to the <a href="http://www.ultraproducts.com/index.php?cPath=38_57" target="_blank" class="postlink">Ultra X-Connect 500</a> which looks to be another sweet power supply. And notice the similar modular design of the power connectors. This also sells for a similar price to the Antec NeoPower but Newegg does not carry it. Reviews of the two power supplies are here at <a href="http://www.tomshardware.com/firstlook/20040720/index.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">Tom's Hardware</a> for the Antec and at <a href="http://www.bjorn3d.com/read.php?cID=711" target="_blank" class="postlink">Bjorn 3d</a> for the Ultra X-Connect. With these two recently released power supplies you only plug in the power connectors for whatever components you need. Everything else can go into storage until you need it. This reduces clutter and having a less cluttered computer case interior means better airflow which leads to cooler running components which improves system stability and lessens the chance of component failures. Also if you have a computer case with a window it also looks a hell of a lot nicer without Medusa's hair do in there. Those who have built computers know what I'm talking about. 
<br />

<br />
As far as an optical drive goes. There is no reason not to get a DVD burner. My recommendation is the NEC ND-3500A or the Pioneer DVR-108. These two run for about 70-80 bucks apiece but they are the best. And $80 is cheaper than when I bought my first DVD burner which was a speedy 4x Pioneer 106 at a low price of $250. You can always add an el-cheapo $30-50 secondary DVD drive at a later date.
<br />

<br />
As far as RAM goes. Look for DDR400 aka PC3200. A 1GB kit should run you about 160-200 dollars. 1GB kits are usually two sticks of 512MB memory. One thing to look for is that it's rated for a CAS latency of 2.5 and not 3. I'm not going to get into a technical discussion on what CAS latency is but suffice to say that it determines how fast information is retrieved and stored on your RAM. The lower it is the faster it is. There are memory rated at CAS 3 that can run at CAS 2.5 but you don't want to take that chance that it won't. Especially since there are CAS 2.5 rated memory that is in the same low end 160-200 dollar price range as the CAS 3 memory.
<br />

<br />
As for a video card. We're not going with the best. A Nvida 6600GT which runs about $200-220 is what we're looking at. If you need to upgrade you can do so at a later date (probably a year down the line) by just buying the same card again and going SLI. At that point the price of the card should have dropped by at least $50. That's the whole beauty of the SLI setup. You can get very high performance upgrading at a later date without having to scrap your old video card if you so choose. You still have the option of upgrading via the traditional route of getting a whole new video card of course. Here is a review of the <a href="http://www.anandtech.com/video/showdoc.aspx?i=2196" target="_blank" class="postlink">Nvidia 6600GT.</a> I'm not going to kid you the 6600GT is a medium range card by todays standards as opposed to the 6800GT. You're not going to be playing many games at the highest setting but almost no one can afford to do that anyways so you're not missing out on much. Hopefully they will release the PCI-X version of the 6800GT in the next two months which will mean that for roughly $400-$500 you can get one of the best video cards out there with the option of upgrading to an SLI configuration later. 
<br />

<br />
Side note: Dual monitors rock. If you have two monitors run it as a dual desktop setup. Trust me. After you use two monitors for a while you will definitely LOVE the extra desktop real estate. I can browse the web on one monitor and watch a dvd on the other or do if you're coding a web page you can monitor how it looks without having to switch programs. Just slide your mouse over to the other monitor. No more visualizing how a page looks and what changes you want done on it. Or constantly having to switch back and forth between programs to see what it looks like. Just look at the other monitor. There are other things you can do as well with two monitors. It does feel awkward at first but once you get a feel for what you like having open on each monitor it is just awesome. I recommend using Ultramon if you do use a two monitor setup.
<br />

<br />
By my estimation without the cost of any software the price is about $1275 with the $50'ish case which is well within your price range. If the PCI-X version of the 6800GT comes out it would still be in the $1500 range which is what you were shooting for. It'd top out at about 1650 for the Lian Li case and 6800GT. All assuming the PCI-X version of the 6800GT comes out in the next roughly two months of course. A secondary DVD drive would put it at about $1700 and another hard drive would bring it to $1800 for a 160-200GB model. That'll put it over your $1500 price point for sure but you only upgrade a full computer once every 4-5 years and what's the fun of not dreaming of parts that go over your budget. <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" /></span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><span style="font-style: italic">On the other hand, if your reaction to something I say boils down to "You didn't choose MY side, make MY choice," well, you're not looking for information, you're looking for someone to tell you how smart you are thinking the way you do. --</span> <span style="font-weight: bold">Ed Stroligo</span></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
