                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Hikaru-
<br />

<br />
I would be carfull with grabing a PCI-X system like that.   It sounds like a great idea with your video card(s) acting like ram aka buy a system with 1 gig today and upgrade in a year when apps start using that much ram.  But changes are your better just buying one chard every 2 years than upgrading your PCI-X system every year. (would need tables to realy show you the math on this one) While PCI-X would let you build a 1000$ graphics card with 2 500$ that blows everything away cards tend to get faster in the sub 400 range so that one 300$ card tends to beat 2 150$ cards.  At lest at the point in the cycle where the new 300$ cards are compaired to the old generation cards.  EX: Right now a x800 pro cost's 30% more than an 9800pro but it's almost 2x as fast.
<br />

<br />
On the other hand with HDD's 3 cheep HDD work better than 2 expencive.
<br />
Western Digital Raptor 74GB 10,000RPM SATA Hard Drive, $182.00
<br />
And a cheep 100$ 200gig drive would only give ya 274GB HDD space and the raptor would still be slower than a raid 5 system with 3 cheep 200gig drives for the same price.  That and if your realy sick you can get 600GB of space at Raptor speeds for 400$ and you don't lose data if one drive fails.  You would probalby want a sever case with 2 power suply's with that many drives though.
<br />

<br />
I tend to work on the 1200$ sytem year 1, 500$ upgrade year 2, new system a year + after that (I try and time it to a good point in the upgrade cycle graphics card / game cycle).  It's ~70$ a month and I can often sell some of my part's  to make that 500$ a major upgrade upgrade (sold off old video card and 512MB PC 2100 memory for 200$ so I could upgrade to a gig of pc 3200 and a geforce 6800 GT) thought about an X800 XT but I am going to get a DVD burner.
<br />

<br />
PS: I like the SATA cables more but I don't  think ATA 133 can slow the system down as your using 133 MB/s cables on drives that only do 35 MB/s (if that) most of the time.  And, I tend to upgrade fast enough that I am not realy worried about geting suck with ATA 133 system in 2 years as by then I am researching my next system.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
