                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Well, you wouldn't be upgrading your PCI-X SLI config every year. What you'd do is buy a medium end to low high end card now (if that makes sense to you). You wait one year when the price drops drastically and buy the same card again. Basically you can buy a $200 dollar video card which is a very good medium end card that will run all the new games. Sure, you're not going to be running those games at the highest resolutions or with all the bells and whistles but 90% of users can't afford the highest end cards anyways so no big loss there. However one year down the line when that card is in the $130'ish range you can buy it again and get a speed boost that would keep your rig well within the medium end range as far as video performance is concerned. You still keep the option of just pulling that card out, selling it and getting a new video card. Multiple upgrade paths work well in real life as well as in games. The upgrade paths work the same way even if you buy a $400 video card as your initial one.
<br />

<br />
By the way, not only is Nvidia the only company working on this. ATI is also rumored to be working on a similar setup and Alienware computers has it's own proprietary setup that is said to work with both ATI and Nvidia cards. I think gpu's (graphics processors), much like cpu's, are hitting a wall in terms of single chip performance and that going forward they will be moving to multiple card or multiple core setups. Even Sony's vaunted Cell processors (the cpu in the upcoming Playstation 3) are at it's heart nothing more than multi-core versions of the PowerPC cpu. That's the same cpu albeit in different versions that run the Nintendo's Gamecube and Apple's computers. 
<br />

<br />
Here are individual non-raid reviews of the Raptor at <a href="http://www.storagereview.com/articles/200401/20040126WD740GD_1.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">Storage Review</a> and at <a href="http://www.anandtech.com/storage/showdoc.aspx?i=2073&p=1" target="_blank" class="postlink">Anandtech</a> that basically say the same thing. As far as single drive IDE/SATA performance is concerned, nothing tops the Raptor. Now RAID setups are a different beast. Most users, even those who are good at computers have no clue how to set up a RAID array and don't even know what the various versions mean. <a href="http://www.storagereview.com/guide2000/ref/hdd/perf/raid/" target="_blank" class="postlink">Redundant Array of Inexpensive Discs</a> is what RAID stands for. Look at <a href="http://www.anandtech.com/storage/showdoc.aspx?i=2101&p=1" target="_blank" class="postlink">this article from Anandtech</a> which basically shows that any performance gain from a RAID 0 config is basically negligable. I really don't see a RAID 5 performing much more differently than a RAID 0 config. RAID 5 is superior because if one hard drive fails there is no risk of data loss but performance wise it's probably on par with RAID 0. The Anandtech article shows gains which are not worth the effort of putting in a RAID array. Also most users do not want a server case and the cost of a second power supply unit negates any cost benefit of a RAID setup. If you can show me an article that says otherwise I'll go take a look at it. I do have a RAID 5 setup but that is for my 1.3TB file server where I keep all my downloaded TV shows and ripped movies and MP3 collection. Having practically the entire library of CSI (or other shows) that you can watch any time 24/7 is priceless. I mean, who really has time to catch a lot of the shows when they air anymore? Except for sunday and monday football games of course. 
<br />

<br />
I agree that the performance difference between ATA (IDE) and SATA are zip at this time. I just like SATA cables much more even if they are a tad stiff as they allow better airflow and are longer. There are rounded IDE cables but testing have shown those to be less reliable than flat IDE cables.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><span style="font-style: italic">On the other hand, if your reaction to something I say boils down to "You didn't choose MY side, make MY choice," well, you're not looking for information, you're looking for someone to tell you how smart you are thinking the way you do. --</span> <span style="font-weight: bold">Ed Stroligo</span></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
