                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Hikaru-
<br />
RAID 5 setup's can be vary vary fast but most low end RAID devices are not built that kind of speed.  First off you need a device that can handle RAID 5 with out acting as a bottle neck.  Something I think the AnandTeck people did I mean 2 raptors is not what a low end RAID system is built to test but they still got "the Raptor RAID-0 array outperforming a single drive by 38%."  But I would have been much more interested in comparing 2 new and cheep drives than having the 2MB IBM drive on that test I mean it's like a 4 year old drive at this point.
<br />

<br />
Anyway... <a href="http://www.tomshardware.com/storage/20040723/raid-scaling-03.html" target="_blank">http://www.tomshardware.com/storage/20040723/raid-scaling-03.html</a>  Shows some testing with a real RAID system using 3 to 8 drives.  Now with out hard data on transfer speeds it's hard to compare but it's easy to see that more drives = faster and cheeper per gig.
<br />

<br />
1 75gig raptor (180$ for 75gig = 2.40$ / gig) 
<br />
3 200Gig Drives (300$ for 400gig = 0.75$ / gig) + full single disk redundancy.
<br />
4 200Gig Drives (400$ for 600gig = 0.66$ / gig) + full single disk redundancy. 
<br />

<br />
So shure 3 drives cost more but your paying 120$ for 325gig's of space.  Which may or may not be worth it for a gaming rig but it's worth thinking about.  You also get a 30% preformance jump going to 4 drives or  20% on the syntetic test's and 200gig's for 100$ which is not bad esp when your increasing the total drive speed by that much.  Now it's not easy to compair the raptor with a non specific drive but as you can see things are vary close.
<br />

<br />
As to PCI-X from what I have heard adding a second card gives you a 40-60% increase in speed.
<br />

<br />
So with your 200$ example you spend 320$ and get 50% more speed in a year + the cost of PCI-X most likely adding up to an extra 100$ but let's be nice and say it's 50$.
<br />

<br />
Well I think you will find a 370$ card that's 50% faster than the 200$ card and you get that extra speed for the first year vs waiting for it.  Then in 2 years you upgrade your one card to something 4x as fast as it and move on.  Once PCI-X is the norm it will be an option worth thinking about for many people. I just don't think spending cash on a PCI-X main bord is worth it right now.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
